state.label: in most silurids, the snout has a smoothly convex dorsal profile and the snout depth gradually decreases anteriorly
in Ceratoglanis and Hemisilurus, the snout is enlarged and the tip is broadened in both lateral and dorsal views
in all other silurids, a supralabial fold covers part of the preorbital area. This fold has a free ventral edge that, with one exception, extends from below the eye to near the maxillary barbel base
in Silurichthys and Pterocryptis, a supralabial fold is absent
in <i>Kyptopterus cryptopterus<i> the supralabial fold is anteriorly truncated such that the lower edge ends far posterior to the maxillary barbel base
orbital rim free
orbital rim not free and eye subcutaneous
in all but one silurid subgroup, the posterior nostril is located anterior to the eye
in Hemisilurus, the posterior nostril is located posterodorsal to the eye
in most silurids, the rictal lobes are at least narrowly continuous at the rictus
in the Wallago leerii, Ompok bimaculatus and O. leiacanthus groups, the rictal lobes are separated by a superficial groove extending from the mouth corner to the submandibular groove
in other silurids, though, a skin fold with a free dorsal edge is present in the upper rictal lobe
in some silurids, the upper rictal lobe lacks a skin fold
in some silurids, though, the submandibular groove extends around the mouth corner only as a shallow indentation

in most silurids, both rictal lobes are deeply subtended by a submandibular groove at the mouth corner and are continuous with each other at the mouth corner, but clearly separate from the surrounding skin
in Pterocryptis and Silurichthys, the submandibular groove does not extend around the mouth corner and at the rictus~both rictal lobes are confluent with the surrounding skin
in all silurids except Ceratoglanis, the maxillary barbel is flexible along its entire length
maxillary barbel in Ceratoglanis is stiffened by a cartilaginous core and distally hooked
two pairs of mental barbels
one pair of mental barbels
plates poorly developed, appearing as areas of diffuse cartilage
plates each with two posterior processes
plates enlarged, roughly circular in shape, and each with a dorsolateral process that contacts the dorsal edge of the anterior ceratohyal
plates enlarged, but elongate and hourglass in shape, without processes

process absent (only Silurichthys Bornbusch, 1991b)
process elongate and slender, extending from the anterior tip of the fourth infraorbital (Fig. 4A)
process elongate, but with a broad origin along the length of the fourth infraorbital (unique to Wullugo attu; Fig. 4B)
process absent (Fig. 4C)

in Cerutoglunis and Hemisilurus, though, a medial gap separates the two bones (state 1; Fig. 6)

extending to middle or anterior third of supraoccipital and covering only medial portion of pterotic
extending to posterior half of supraethmoid and lateral ethmoid and covering entire frontal (unique to Belodontichthys)
most subgroups have gill-raker counts greater than ten on the outermost arch
in Pterocryptis and Silurichthys, gill rakers on the outermost arch are maximally 11 and usually less than 10
ceratohyals joined by an interdigitating suture that develops with growth on the lateral and, in subgroups, medial surfaces of the bones

the ventral surface of the premaxilla is fully toothed
